revision.text:
'''Kaisei School''' (開成学校) was an early Meiji-era educational institution under the jurisdiction of the {{ill|Ministry of Education|ja|文部省|12=draft}}, located in Tokyo Prefecture. It was one of the "specialized schools" of the time, representing higher education distinct from later vocational schools under the {{ill|Senmon Gakkō Rei|ja|専門学校令|12=draft}}.  
[[File:Kaisei School1.jpg|thumb|right|270px|The later Kaisei School (1873)]]

== Overview ==  
Kaisei School, as a government institution in early Meiji Japan, can be divided into two main periods: the "Early Kaisei School" (1868–1870) and the "Later Kaisei School" (1872–1877).  

The early phase began with the revival of the {{ill|Kaiseijo|ja|開成所|12=draft}}, a school for foreign studies established in 1863 by the {{ill|Tokugawa shogunate|ja|Tokugawa shogunate|12=draft}} but closed after the {{ill|Fall of Edo|ja|江戸開城|12=draft}} in 1868. The new Meiji government reopened it in September 1868 as Kaisei School.  

The later phase began in 1872 when the {{ill|University South Campus|ja|大学南校|12=draft}} was reorganized as the First University District First Middle School. Renamed Kaisei School in 1873, it later became Tokyo Kaisei School and was integrated with {{ill|Tokyo Medical School|ja|東京医学校|12=draft}} in 1877 to form the {{ill|(Old) Tokyo University|ja|東京大学 (1877-1886)|12=draft}}.  

Kaisei School also influenced the establishment of the {{ill|Meirokusha|ja|明六社|12=draft}} in 1873, where many of its faculty and students were active members.  

== History ==  

=== Origins: Tokugawa Kaiseijo ===  
{{Main|Kaiseijo}}  
Kaisei School traces its roots to the {{ill|Bansho Shirabesho|ja|蕃書調所|12=draft}}, established in 1857 by the Tokugawa shogunate to study and teach Western knowledge. Renamed {{ill|Kaiseijo|ja|開成所|12=draft}} in 1863, it became the direct predecessor of Kaisei School.  

=== Early Kaisei School ===  
{{wikisource|Newspaper Printing Ordinance}}  
The Kaiseijo was temporarily closed during the {{ill|Meiji Restoration|ja|明治維新|12=draft}} in 1868 but reopened by the Meiji government on September 12, 1868 (Lunisolar September12日). Officially renamed Kaisei School on January 17, 1869 (明治2nd year 1月17日), it resumed as a center for Western learning and translation under Dutch missionary {{ill|Guido Verbeck|ja|グイド・フルベッキ|12=draft}}, who served as vice-principal.  

Courses were offered in English, German, and French, reflecting the languages of the foreign instructors. In July 1869, the school became part of the {{ill|University|ja|大学校|12=draft}}, later renamed the {{ill|University South Campus|ja|大学南校|12=draft}} in 1870.  

=== University South Campus ===  
{{Main|University South Campus}}  
After internal conflicts caused the closure of the {{ill|University Main Campus|ja|大学本校|12=draft}} in August 1870, the South Campus effectively operated independently. It emphasized educating {{ill|Gongin Students|ja|貢進生|12=draft}}, elite students chosen from across Japan to study English, French, or German.  

In 1871, the campus was renamed "Nanko" and briefly closed for reorganization. It reopened later that year, focusing on general foreign language education.  

=== Later Kaisei School (Tokyo Kaisei School) ===  
In 1872, Nanko was reorganized as the First University District First Middle School under the new {{ill|Education System Order|ja|学制|12=draft}}. By 1873, it transitioned into Kaisei School, with English as the primary language of instruction. The curriculum expanded to include five specialized courses: law, chemistry, engineering, mining, and arts, though French and German continued in limited capacities.  

In November 1873, the foreign language department separated to form the {{ill|Tokyo Foreign Language School|ja|東京外国語学校 (旧制)|12=draft}}, a precursor to the {{ill|Tokyo University of Foreign Studies|ja|東京外国語大学|12=draft}}.  

Renamed Tokyo Kaisei School in 1874, it added a preparatory department and courses for practical engineering training. In 1875, the first group of government-sponsored overseas students, selected from its Ranks, began their studies abroad.  

By 1877, Tokyo Kaisei School merged with Tokyo Medical School to form {{ill|(Old) Tokyo University|ja|東京大学 (1877-1886)|12=draft}}, contributing its law, science, and literature departments.  

== Notable Alumni ==  
* {{ill|Kikuchi Takeo (lawyer)|ja|菊池武夫 (法律家)|12=draft}}  
* {{ill|Hozumi Nobushige|ja|穂積陳重|12=draft}}  
* {{ill|Hatoyama Kazuo|ja|鳩山和夫|12=draft}}  
* {{ill|Miyake Setsurei|ja|三宅雪嶺|12=draft}}  
* {{ill|Jigorō Kanō|ja|嘉納治五郎|12=draft}}  
* {{ill|Yamaguchi Hanroku|ja|山口半六|12=draft}}  
* {{ill|Natsume Sōseki|ja|夏目漱石|12=draft}} (elder brother Natsume Daisuke)  

== Faculty ==  
* {{ill|Guido Verbeck|ja|グイド・フルベッキ|12=draft}}  
* {{ill|Gottfried Wagener|ja|ゴットフリード・ワグネル|12=draft}}  
* {{ill|Nakayama Manjirō|ja|中浜万次郎|12=draft}} (John Manjirō)  

== Campus and Legacy ==  
The school operated at its original location in {{ill|Kanda Hitotsubashi|ja|神田一ツ橋|12=draft}}, later moving to the {{ill|Hongo Campus|ja|東京大学本郷地区キャンパス|12=draft}} by 1885. A monument commemorating "The Birthplace of the University of Tokyo" stands at the original site.  

== Related Literature ==  
; Books  
* Masao Terasaki, ''The History of the University of Tokyo: Pioneer of the University System,'' Kodansha Academic Library, 2007 ISBN 9784061597990  
* Ikuo Amano, ''The Birth of Universities (Part I): The Era of Imperial Universities,'' Chuko Shinsho, 2009 ISBN 9784121020048  

== Related Articles ==  
* {{ill|Meirokusha|ja|明六社|12=draft}}  
* {{ill|Tokyo Foreign Language School (Meiji)|ja|東京外国語学校 (旧制)|12=draft}}  

